Calculating the equilibrium constant

Adapted from DBE Nov 2015 Grade 12, P2, Q6
Physical constants ·· Chemistry formulas ·· Periodic table ·· Standard reduction potentials

An unknown gas, D2(g), is sealed in a container and allowed to form D3(g) at 300°C300°C. The reaction reaches equilibrium according to the following balanced equation:

3D2(g) ⇌⇌ 2D3(g)

  1. How will the rate of formation of D3(g) compare to the rate of formation of D2(g) at equilibrium?

    Answer:

    The rate of formation of D3(g) will be the rate of formation of D2(g) at equilibrium.

  2. The reaction mixture is analysed at regular time intervals. The results obtained are shown in the table below.

    1515 0,210,21 0,320,32

    Calculate the equilibrium constant, 𝐾cKc, for this reaction at 300°C300°C.

    Answer:

    𝐾c=Kc=

Chemical equilibrium: definitions

Give one word or term for the following definition:

A chemical reaction that can proceed in both the forward and reverse directions. In other words, the reactants and products of the reaction may reverse roles.

The Haber process

In industry it is important to get the desired products of a reaction quickly and cheaply. One very important industrial reaction is the Haber process to make ammonia. The reaction for this process is:

3H2(g)+N2(g)⇋2NH3(g)+ energy3H2(g)+N2(g)⇋2NH3(g)+ energy

This reaction takes place in the presence of an iron (Fe) catalyst under high pressure (200 atm200 atm) and temperature (450°C450°C - 500°C500°C) conditions. The ammonia is also removed as it is formed.

    • 15°C15°C
    • 115°C115°C
    • 65°C65°C

    B remove the ammonia from the reaction vessel after some time
    C increase the concentration of the ammonia
